## Scope

This slice delivers the final Part J tranche and is the LAST slice of the arc: the [Standard] long-running job progress/cancellation/timing harness (J.10), the [Standard] in-app help/glossary/onboarding gallery (J.11), and the [Standard] 2D/3D rendered system/beam view (J.12). As the last slice it carries the full gate set (as do all slices).

§J.10 `JobRunner` is the single shared background-job harness that hosts heavy sweeps (`calculate`/`calculate3D`, `Variables.fs:237,270`) and Part G fit runs; slice 011 (§G.10) supplies the per-iteration optimizer progress payload to it, and an active job appears in the `AppShell` (J.8) shared status area from slice 015. §J.12 `SystemView3D` delivers the custom OpenTK system/beam viewport RESERVED by Part A §A.6 — it consumes that reservation and is distinct from the §J.1 Avalonia-`Canvas` schematic (slice 014) and the §E.4/§H.8 Poincaré OpenTK use; it consumes the already-solved beam tree and MUST NOT re-solve or re-route. UI-touching (FuncUI/OpenTK) — relies on the slice-001 buildable interpretation.

## Requirements

### R-1. §J.10 Long-running job progress, cancellation & timing [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide a `JobRunner` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/JobRunner.fs`) that runs heavy sweeps and optimizations (the engine calls `calculate`/`calculate3D` `Variables.fs:237,270` for sweeps, and Part G's ALGLIB path for fits) on a background worker with progress, cancellation, and elapsed-time reporting, surfaced as MVU messages. This is the single shared background-job harness; Part G §G.10 supplies the per-iteration optimizer progress payload to it. Because this introduces a long-running, cancellable background job, the operator-facing UX checklist is discharged here:

1. **Discoverability/nav entry.** Every long job MUST be launched from a labelled control on its owning page (the sweep panel, the fit panel), and an active job MUST appear in a single shared status area in `AppShell` (J.8) so it is discoverable regardless of which panel started it.
2. **Progress granularity.** Progress MUST be reported as completed-points-over-total for sweeps (driven by the `RangedVariable` point count, `Variables.fs:42`) and as iteration count for optimization; a job whose total is unknown MUST show an indeterminate-but-running state, never a frozen UI.
3. **Pre-confirmation vs one-click.** Starting a sweep/fit MUST be one-click (it is non-destructive and recomputable). Cancellation, by contrast, MUST be immediate one-click with no confirmation, since the partial result is discardable.
4. **Completion → results refresh.** On job completion the runner MUST emit a completion message that triggers the owning page's results/chart refresh through the normal MVU `update` → `view` cycle; results MUST NOT require a manual reload.
5. **Opposing-action button + undo.** The Start control MUST become a Cancel control for the duration of the job (single button, two states) so the opposing action is unambiguous; cancelling MUST leave the prior committed results untouched (the cancelled job's partial output is dropped, which is the natural undo).
6. **Committable file vs .gitignore.** Any derived artefact a job writes (sweep/field-map `.binz` sidecars, fit histories) MUST be written under the project's sidecar directory referenced from the project JSON (§A.7), NOT into the repository root; these are derived outputs and Part J MUST NOT add them as committable project files.

Cancellation MUST be cooperative via a `System.Threading.CancellationToken` checked between sweep points / optimizer iterations; killing threads, retry-on-failure loops, and a job queue/scheduler abstraction are OUT OF SCOPE (§0 constraint 6) — one job per worker, cancel-and-restart is the model.

### R-2. §J.11 In-app help, glossary & onboarding gallery [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide a `Help` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Help.fs`) delivering: an in-app material/units glossary and field tooltips, plus a gallery of worked examples and getting-started sample projects shipped with the app. The gallery MUST be built from the engine's existing example scripts in `C:/GitHub/Berreman/Berreman/Analytics/Examples/` — at minimum the AR/multilayer, DBR/EUV Mo-Si, active-crystal, wedge, and dispersive-glass cases, which exist as `MultilayerThinFilm.fsx`, `MultilayerThinFilm_EUV.fsx`, `ActiveCrystal.fsx`, `Wedge_Glass.fsx`/`Wedge_BiaxialCrystal.fsx`, and `Glass_Dispersive.fsx` respectively. Each gallery entry MUST open as a normal `OpticalConstructorProject` through the Part I open path (§I.3 `openProject`, so schema validation applies, §A.7) — the `.fsx` files are the design reference for the equivalent shipped sample projects and MUST NOT be executed at runtime by the app. The units glossary MUST state the canonical boundary conversions from §A.10 (eV via `E[eV] = 1239.84 / λ[nm]`, cm⁻¹ via wavenumber) and MUST NOT introduce a second conversion implementation. Tooltips are static strings co-located in `Help.fs`; an authorable/markdown help-content pipeline is OUT OF SCOPE.

### R-3. §J.12 2D/3D rendered view of the element/system with the beam path [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide a `SystemView3D` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/SystemView3D.fs`) that delivers 010 §1's [Standard] "2D/3D rendered view of the element/system with the beam path" (010 line 127), rendered in the custom OpenTK 3D viewport Part A reserves for exactly this surface in the `OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` row (§A.1, §A.6) — this is the part that consumes that reservation. The view MUST draw, to scale, the placed `ConstructorElement`s of the open project's `BeamTree`/`BeamNode` topology (§A.4) — sample, mirror, lens, polarizer, analyzer, detector — positioned along the beam path, and MUST draw the beam path itself as the reflected/transmitted ray segments routed by the beam tree, reading each segment's direction from the solved `EmFieldSystem.reflected`/`.transmitted` (`Fields.fs:553-554`) that Part B already produces (§B.1, §B.4). This part MUST NOT re-solve the system or re-derive beam routing: it consumes the already-solved beam tree and renders it. Geometry MUST read canonical SI (meters) from the domain values and convert to viewport coordinates only at the render boundary (§A.3); no converted value MAY be written back into the model.

The OpenTK renderer here is distinct from, and MUST NOT duplicate, two existing surfaces: the [Core] 2D schematic cross-section of a single stack (§J.1, an Avalonia `Canvas`) and the Poincaré-sphere OpenTK use named for the polarization picker/charts (§E.4, §H.8). This `SystemView3D` is the system/beam viewport; §H.8's Poincaré rendering and §H.5's reservation note ("Custom OpenTK 3D rendering is reserved by Part A for the system/beam viewport and MUST NOT be used here") both refer to this same reserved viewport, now delivered here. This part MUST NOT add full 3D vector wave optics, diffraction rendering, or a second physics engine (Part A §A.5); the rendered beam segments are the straight ray/beam paths the orchestration already carries. A retained-mode scene-graph abstraction, level-of-detail, and camera-state persistence beyond the §J.6 panel-layout fields are OUT OF SCOPE.

## Non-requirements

- Schematic / repeat builder / templates / drag-drop / comparison workspace are Part J §J.1–J.5, owned by slice 014.
- Persistent environment/favorites, preferences, theme/dockable panels, and the J.9 validation seam are Part J §J.6–J.9, owned by slice 015; the `AppShell` shared job-status area J.10 item 1 references is supplied by slice 015.
- Full 3D vector wave optics, diffraction rendering, or a second physics engine are OUT OF SCOPE (§J.12, Part A §A.5); the rendered beam segments are the straight ray/beam paths the orchestration already carries.
- A retained-mode scene-graph / level-of-detail / camera-state persistence beyond the §J.6 panel-layout fields are OUT OF SCOPE (§J.12).
- Killing threads / retry-on-failure loops / a job queue-scheduler abstraction are OUT OF SCOPE (§J.10 — one job per worker, cancel-and-restart).
- An authorable/markdown help-content pipeline is OUT OF SCOPE (§J.11); tooltips are static strings co-located in `Help.fs`, and `.fsx` files MUST NOT be executed at runtime.

